<paragraph blockId="2.[151,555,1717,1776]" box="[151,367,1751,1776]" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">
<figureCitation box="[151,285,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,203,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Oncopsis spp., lateral view and face. 1 – 5 ― O. sulphurea (1 and 4 – 5 ― male from the mainland, 2 – 3 ― specimens from Shikotan, Kurile Islands), 6 – 9 ― O. nitobei, 10 – 15 ― O. furva, paratypes, 16 – 20 ― O. sepulcralis, 21 – 23 ― O. discrepans, 24 – 26 ― O. caliginosa, 27 – 28 ― O. wagneri, 29 – 32 ― O. ochotensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242422/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Figs. 10–15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[297,367,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 80" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1831,1854]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,212,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1811]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 80. Oncopsis spp., male genitalia. 50 – 63 ― O. sulphurea, 64 – 68 ― O. nitobei, 69 – 71 ― O. furva, paratype, 72 – 76 ― O. sepulcralis, 77 – 80 ― O. discrepans. 59, 64, 69, 72, 77 ― penis, caudal view, 60 ― penis, lateral view, 61, 65, 70, 73, 78 ― penis and dorsal connective, lateral view, 62, 66 – 67, 74, 79 ― lower appendage of dorsal connective, lateral view, 63, 68, 71, 75 – 76, 80 ― style, broadest aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242424/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">69–71</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1823,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1823,1848]" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Description.</emphasis>
Face yellow with dark pattern; all spots merged with each other (
<figureCitation box="[1065,1204,1823,1848]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,203,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Oncopsis spp., lateral view and face. 1 – 5 ― O. sulphurea (1 and 4 – 5 ― male from the mainland, 2 – 3 ― specimens from Shikotan, Kurile Islands), 6 – 9 ― O. nitobei, 10 – 15 ― O. furva, paratypes, 16 – 20 ― O. sepulcralis, 21 – 23 ― O. discrepans, 24 – 26 ― O. caliginosa, 27 – 28 ― O. wagneri, 29 – 32 ― O. ochotensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242422/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Figs. 13–15</figureCitation>
). In males and dark females pro- and mesonotum almost entirely black (
<figureCitation box="[749,886,1860,1885]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,203,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Oncopsis spp., lateral view and face. 1 – 5 ― O. sulphurea (1 and 4 – 5 ― male from the mainland, 2 – 3 ― specimens from Shikotan, Kurile Islands), 6 – 9 ― O. nitobei, 10 – 15 ― O. furva, paratypes, 16 – 20 ― O. sepulcralis, 21 – 23 ― O. discrepans, 24 – 26 ― O. caliginosa, 27 – 28 ― O. wagneri, 29 – 32 ― O. ochotensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242422/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Figs. 10–11</figureCitation>
). In light females pronotum yellow with typical dark pattern, but mesonotum retains almost black coloration (
<figureCitation box="[906,998,1895,1920]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,203,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Oncopsis spp., lateral view and face. 1 – 5 ― O. sulphurea (1 and 4 – 5 ― male from the mainland, 2 – 3 ― specimens from Shikotan, Kurile Islands), 6 – 9 ― O. nitobei, 10 – 15 ― O. furva, paratypes, 16 – 20 ― O. sepulcralis, 21 – 23 ― O. discrepans, 24 – 26 ― O. caliginosa, 27 – 28 ― O. wagneri, 29 – 32 ― O. ochotensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242422/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Forewings strongly infumose with transparent areas at end of clavus and along costal margin; in light specimens claval suture also transparent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1823,2029]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,752]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="540" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">
Penis of typical shape, with ventral margin convex in side view (
<figureCitation box="[958,1099,1968,1993]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 80" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1831,1854]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,212,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1811]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 80. Oncopsis spp., male genitalia. 50 – 63 ― O. sulphurea, 64 – 68 ― O. nitobei, 69 – 71 ― O. furva, paratype, 72 – 76 ― O. sepulcralis, 77 – 80 ― O. discrepans. 59, 64, 69, 72, 77 ― penis, caudal view, 60 ― penis, lateral view, 61, 65, 70, 73, 78 ― penis and dorsal connective, lateral view, 62, 66 – 67, 74, 79 ― lower appendage of dorsal connective, lateral view, 63, 68, 71, 75 – 76, 80 ― style, broadest aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242424/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="539">Figs. 69–70</figureCitation>
). Lower appendage of dorsal connective bifurcated, both branches with finely serrated inner margins, upper branch distinctly longer than lower one, notch between the branches is more or less elongated (
<figureCitation box="[832,918,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 80" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1831,1854]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,212,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1811]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 80. Oncopsis spp., male genitalia. 50 – 63 ― O. sulphurea, 64 – 68 ― O. nitobei, 69 – 71 ― O. furva, paratype, 72 – 76 ― O. sepulcralis, 77 – 80 ― O. discrepans. 59, 64, 69, 72, 77 ― penis, caudal view, 60 ― penis, lateral view, 61, 65, 70, 73, 78 ― penis and dorsal connective, lateral view, 62, 66 – 67, 74, 79 ― lower appendage of dorsal connective, lateral view, 63, 68, 71, 75 – 76, 80 ― style, broadest aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242424/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
). Style parallel-margined, with acute tip (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 80" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1831,1854]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,212,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1811]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 80. Oncopsis spp., male genitalia. 50 – 63 ― O. sulphurea, 64 – 68 ― O. nitobei, 69 – 71 ― O. furva, paratype, 72 – 76 ― O. sepulcralis, 77 – 80 ― O. discrepans. 59, 64, 69, 72, 77 ― penis, caudal view, 60 ― penis, lateral view, 61, 65, 70, 73, 78 ― penis and dorsal connective, lateral view, 62, 66 – 67, 74, 79 ― lower appendage of dorsal connective, lateral view, 63, 68, 71, 75 – 76, 80 ― style, broadest aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242424/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[199,942,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">
Body length (including tegmina): ♂, 
<quantity box="[615,753,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="4.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" unit="mm" value="4.4" valueMax="4.6" valueMin="4.2">4.2–4.6 mm</quantity>
; ♀, 
<quantity box="[799,937,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="4.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" unit="mm" value="4.8" valueMax="4.9" valueMin="4.7">4.7–4.9 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">
Differs from most other Russian species by dark coloration; in external appearance somewhat similar with 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitobei">O. nitobei</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[247,409,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">O. sepulcralis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and dark males of 
<taxonomicName box="[653,803,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulphurea">
<emphasis box="[653,803,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">O. sulphurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[823,968,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,203,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Oncopsis spp., lateral view and face. 1 – 5 ― O. sulphurea (1 and 4 – 5 ― male from the mainland, 2 – 3 ― specimens from Shikotan, Kurile Islands), 6 – 9 ― O. nitobei, 10 – 15 ― O. furva, paratypes, 16 – 20 ― O. sepulcralis, 21 – 23 ― O. discrepans, 24 – 26 ― O. caliginosa, 27 – 28 ― O. wagneri, 29 – 32 ― O. ochotensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242422/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">Figs. 1, 6–7</figureCitation>
, and 16–17). In the shape of the lower appendage of dorsal connective similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[652,814,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">
<emphasis box="[652,814,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">O. sepulcralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by elongated notch between branches of appendage (more or less round in 
<taxonomicName box="[532,689,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Oncopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">
<emphasis box="[532,689,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="540">O. sepulcralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and host preference.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
